What is an array.

An array is a fixed-size, contiguous block of memory where every element is the same type and therefore the same size. Elements are stored one after another with no gaps between them.

This layout enables the key property of arrays: constant time random access. To find the element at any index, the processor computes its memory address with simple arithmetic — the base address plus the index multiplied by the element size. No searching, no pointer-chasing — just a single calculation. Whether the index is zero or ten million, that calculation takes the same number of steps.

Picture a row of identical numbered lockers in a corridor. You know the first locker is at position one hundred. Every locker is the same width — say, four units. To reach locker fifty, you go to position one hundred plus fifty times four. You do not walk past lockers one through forty-nine — you jump directly to the right spot. That is exactly how array indexing works.
